optimization_guidance.statistics_queries: Full spatial domain (single timestep): use quality -4 to -6 as the default sweet spot. Measured times on full domain, single timestep: mean at q=-4 took 22.51 s; max at q=-4 took 19.92 s; mean at q=-6 took 9.33 s; max at q=-6 took 9.81 s; p20 at q=-4 took 32.76 s and at q=-6 took 12.77 s. Avoid q=-1 and q=0 for full-domain stats; they failed with memory errors in our tests. If you must run near-full-accuracy (q=-2), expect 67.06 s (max), 128.27 s (mean), 154.40 s (p20). Regional stats (small/medium windows): time is dominated by fixed overhead and is ~1.051.43 s regardless of quality. For small 200x200 windows: mean at q=0 took 1.38 s and at q=-6 took 1.36 s. For medium 500x500 windows: mean at q=0 took 1.37 s and at q=-6 took 1.26 s. Therefore, for regional stats prefer higher quality (-1 or 0) because the time penalty is negligible. Large regional (1000x1000) single timestep: q=-6 completed in 1.31 s vs q=0 in 2.07 s; use q=-6 by default unless you need exactness.
optimization_guidance.analytics_queries: For multi-timestep full-domain analytics (correlations, trends), quality -6 offers the best time-to-coverage tradeoff and scales close to linearly with timesteps. Measured full-domain times: 2 timesteps: q=-6 16.87 s (vs q=-4 30.98 s, q=-2 126.21 s). 7 timesteps: q=-6 54.27 s (vs q=-4 111.69 s, q=-2 462.62 s). 30 timesteps: q=-6 227.71 s (~3.8 min) (vs q=-4 462.98 s, q=-2 2836.15 s  47 min). Single-timestep full-domain analytics: q=-6 7.809.81 s depending on metric (see stats above). Regional analytics across small windows scale almost linearly with timestep count and remain fast at high quality: small region (100x100) 5 timesteps at q=0 = 6.43 s; 10 timesteps at q=0 = 13.61 s. Prefer high quality (-1 or 0) for regional analytics because overhead dominates time and accuracy benefits are high. For large regional (1000x1000) time series, q=-6 is a good default (1.31 s per timestep); consider q=-1/0 only if you truly need full detail.
optimization_guidance.temporal_sampling: Time cost per timestep is approximately linear at fixed quality. Using q=-6 on full domain: ~8.4 s per timestep (single-timestep ~7.809.81 s; 2 steps 16.87 s; 7 steps 54.27 s; 30 steps 227.71 s). Use temporal subsampling when analysis tolerates coarser cadence: e.g., downsample by 24x in time to cut wall time similarly. If you need many timesteps within ~1 minute on full domain: at q=-6 you can cover ~67 timesteps (~54 s for 7). To cover 30 timesteps in ~1 minute, reduce spatial scope (regional subset) or drop quality further (q=-8: 30-step multi-timestep not measured, but single-step speedups at q=-8 are 3475x vs q=-2; expect ~45x faster than q=-6 at the cost of heavy accuracy loss). For regional windows, 10 timesteps at q=0 small region took 13.61 s; scale linearly for longer runs.
optimization_guidance.spatial_sampling: Spatial subsetting yields the largest time savings when feasible. Small (200x200) and medium (500x500) windows run in ~1.051.37 s per timestep nearly regardless of quality (q=-15..0). Use the highest needed quality (-1 or 0) for regional queries since time impact is minimal. For large regional (1000x1000) single timesteps: q=-6 was 1.31 s vs q=0 2.07 s; choose q=-6 by default unless exactness is required. For full-domain queries, avoid q=-1 and q=0 due to repeated memory allocation failures; default to q=-6 for analytics and q=-4 to -6 for statistics. If minute-level budgets are strict and full-domain is required, consider q=-8 (single-step full-domain: 1.531.94 s depending on op) while recognizing it samples ~1.67% of full data.

processing_insights.primary_bottleneck: Memory/I-O. Evidence: full-domain q=-1/0 repeatedly failed with 'cannot allocate buffer'. Memory use at full-domain q=-2 was very high (single step ~4805 MB; 2 steps ~9610 MB; 7 steps ~33,635 MB; 30 steps ~144,150 MB). Throughput rises with data volume (~1021M pts/s at moderate quality) and small/medium regional queries are dominated by fixed overhead (~1.051.37 s regardless of data), indicating I/O/setup costs dominate for small regions and memory bandwidth/capacity dominates for full domain.
processing_insights.time_expectations: Full-domain single timestep: q=-6  7.809.81 s; q=-5  10.1016.80 s; q=-4  19.9232.76 s; q=-2  67.06128.27 s depending on operation. Full-domain multi-timestep: 2 steps q=-6 16.87 s; 7 steps q=-6 54.27 s; 30 steps q=-6 227.71 s; at q=-4: 30.98 s, 111.69 s, 462.98 s; at q=-2: 126.21 s, 462.62 s, 2836.15 s. Regional small/medium per timestep: ~1.051.37 s across qualities. Large 1000x1000 single timestep: q=-6 1.31 s; q=-4 1.34 s; q=-1 1.66 s; q=0 2.07 s.
processing_insights.optimization_priority: 1) Avoid q=-1 and q=0 for full-domain to prevent memory failures. 2) Choose quality first (q=-6 default for analytics; q=-4 to -6 for statistics), then reduce spatial extent if possible, then reduce temporal coverage or subsample time. 3) For small/medium regions, run high quality (-1 or 0) since time is overhead-limited. 4) For quantiles (e.g., p20), expect extra compute overhead: at single-step full-domain q=-4, mean=22.51 s vs p20=32.76 s; factor this into budgets.

usage_recommendations: Global mean/max over full domain, one timestep: use q=-6 when you need sub-10 s results (mean 9.33 s; max 9.81 s measured). If you need a bit more fidelity, q=-4 yields mean 22.51 s and max 19.92 s.
Global quantile (p20) is slower than mean/max. One timestep, full domain: q=-6 took 12.77 s; q=-4 took 32.76 s. Choose q=-6 by default for quantiles unless accuracy demands q=-4.
Two-timestep full-domain analytics (e.g., correlation across t0,t1): q=-6 finished in 16.87 s; q=-4 took 30.98 s; q=-2 took 126.21 s.
Seven-timestep full-domain trend: q=-6  54.27 s; q=-4  111.69 s; q=-2  462.62 s.
Thirty-timestep full-domain trend: q=-6  227.71 s (~3.8 min); q=-4  462.98 s (~7.7 min); q=-2  2836.15 s (~47 min).
Small regional stats (200x200xfull depth), one timestep: mean at q=0 1.38 s; q=-6 1.36 s; choose high quality (q=-1/0) since time is nearly the same.
Medium regional stats (500x500), one timestep: mean q=0 1.37 s; q=-6 1.26 s; high quality is practical.
Large regional (1000x1000), one timestep: q=-6 1.31 s vs q=0 2.07 s; use q=-6 by default for speed.
Small region multi-timestep: 5 steps at q=0 took 6.43 s; 10 steps at q=0 took 13.61 s. For regional time series, prefer q=-1/0 for fidelity; time scales nearly linearly with steps.
Full-domain single-timestep at aggressive downsampling: q=-8 ran in 1.531.94 s across ops (mean 1.99 s, max 1.94 s) but samples ~1.67% of data; use only for exploratory scans.
potential_issues: Memory allocation failures at full-domain q=-1 and q=0 across single and multi-timestep tests; avoid these quality levels on full domain.
High memory footprint at q=-2 with many timesteps (e.g., 30-timestep full-domain used ~144 GB), which may exceed system limits.
Quantile operations (e.g., p20) have higher computation overhead than mean/min/max at the same quality (e.g., single-step full-domain q=-4: mean 22.51 s vs p20 32.76 s).
Small/medium regional queries are overhead-limited (~1.051.37 s) so gains from lowering quality are minimal; plan for that fixed latency.
Accuracy decreases rapidly as quality becomes more aggressive (e.g., q=-6 retains ~6.39% of data vs full). Choose quality with care for sensitive statistics.
accuracy_tradeoffs: Relative to full-resolution q=-2 baseline (100% data): q=-4 retains ~25.56% of data at ~3.45.7x faster for single-step full-domain (e.g., max: 67.06 s  19.92 s; mean: 128.27 s  22.51 s).
q=-5 retains ~12.78% of data at ~5.79.8x faster for single-step full-domain (e.g., max: 67.06 s  11.85 s; mean: 128.27 s  13.06 s; p20: 154.40 s  16.80 s).

q=-6 retains ~6.39% of data at ~6.813.7x faster for single-step full-domain (max 9.81 s; mean 9.33 s; p20 12.77 s). This is the recommended default for multi-timestep analytics due to best time-to-coverage.
q=-8 retains ~1.67% of data at dramatic speedups (single-step full-domain: mean 1.99 s; max 1.94 s); use for fast exploratory scans where coarse accuracy is acceptable.
Multi-timestep full-domain scales near-linearly with steps at fixed quality: at q=-6, 2730 steps took 16.8754.27227.71 s, enabling predictable budgeting.
Regional small/medium windows: time ~1.051.37 s regardless of quality; therefore choose higher quality (-1/0) to maximize accuracy since time savings from lower quality are negligible.
